<br>
<br>
1.  How the hell does a Guide have authority to OVERRULE the decision of the HEAD GM?<br>
<br>
In this case, it has nothing to do with overruling the decision of a Head GM.  Whoever is doing the surname approval be it a guide or GM will take a look at the name and make a decision based on what they know.  Some guides or GM's might be well versed enough in other languages or even pop culture to know when the Naming Policy is being broken, some guides/GM's are not.  Its that simple.  <br>
<br>
When any guide/GM 'sees' a player with an illegal name, they MUST report it whether they want to or not.  Additionally, if it's a class 1 or 2 violation, it gets changed.  Period.  It doesnt matter if its a Homonym, Synonym, in some Foreign Language, written backwards, upside down, or word jumbled.  I'm sure you get the idea now.  For any other class violations, if the character is level 35, the name is reported but beyond that its VI's responsibility to decide what to do.<br>
<br>
2. What possible way can you be sure that your name is ACCEPTABLE by all GMs Guides and any other wannabe Verant employees on a powertrip?<br>
<br>
Choose something normal.  You know, a name you can find &quot;Baby's Book of Names&quot; that you can pick up for 50 cents in the grocery store.  Or perhaps something out of the phone book.  Don't choose people that you've read out of book, seen in a movie, watched on TV, read in a newspaper or magazine.  Chances are a guide or GM has seen it too.  <br>
<br>
No matter how tempting, stop picking a first and last name that sounds 'cute' together.  Technically all such names are illegal when they make a phrase.  <br>
<br>
<br>
On a related issue is my own personal opinion on the naming policy.  I have no problem with it.  It was well thought out and well meant.  I can see why Verant has it and why they enforce it.  After seeing another &quot;Dark Lord of the Sith&quot; running around in Ultima Online, I think naming guidelines are a good thing.  Yes, perhaps Verant has been inconsistent but I maintain they are trying to BE consistent everytime they enforce it.  <br>
<br>
Its very easy to get all up in arms over this matter (any policy even) but the fact is, they have the rule, live with it.  You obviously were aware of the rule so if you get caught breaking it, you have no ground to stand on.  If you dont like the rules of the game, then don't play.  <br>
<br>
How easy it is to blame the guide, blame Verant, and never accept even a little bit of the blame yourself.  <br>
<br>
